    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, provide a compact overview: total row count, minimum timestamp, maximum timestamp, and the top 20 cmdb_id values with their counts. Also list the distinct KPI/trace/log name fields present (up to 50 names) for each file (metric.csv: kpi_name; trace.csv: trace_name; log.csv: log_name; error_logs.csv: none). For metric.csv: aggregate by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) over the full available series (do NOT filter by time) and compute count, P50, P95, and P99 of the 'value' column; return the top 20 rows sorted by count with columns [cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, p50, p95, p99]. For trace.csv and log.csv: aggregate similarly by (cmdb_id, trace_name)/(cmdb_id, log_name) and compute count, P50, P95, and P99 of 'value'; return top 20 by count for each. Finally, using timezone UTC+8, filter each file to the time window from '2022-03-21 07:30:00' to '2022-03-21 08:00:00' (inclusive start, exclusive end) and report the number of rows in that window for each file. Keep all outputs compact and bounded (at most 20 rows where applicable). Store full intermediate tables in kernel variables but do not print them." }

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) over the full metric series and then detected per-series breaches inside the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00–08:00:00 (UTC+8). The metric scan found 5,298 distinct series and 1,393 series with at least one breach inside the window. The compact top examples show many mesh and container KPIs with multiple breaches; notable candidates include network receive on checkoutservice-1, several mesh destination/source KPIs for currencyservice and frontend, and node-6 system CPU/iowait/io wait metrics with strong severity. These point toward both node-level resource issues (node-6 io/iowait/cpu) and container/network anomalies (container network receive on checkoutservice-1 and mesh traffic metrics). We must now convert per-point anomalies into 'faults' (consecutive anomalous minutes) and summarize per-component fault counts and earliest fault times so we can choose a small set of candidates for trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric series (kernel variable metric dataframe) and the previously computed per-series P95/P5 thresholds (kernel variable metric thresholds table), detect consecutive anomalous segments (faults) inside the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 (inclusive) to 2022-03-21 08:00:00 (exclusive) UTC+8. Define an anomalous row as value > P95 (type='high') or value < P5 (type='low'). Then group consecutive timestamps (consecutive minutes) of the same series and same type into one fault. For each fault produce one row with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_type (high/low), start_ts (earliest ts in fault, UTC+8), end_ts (latest ts in fault, UTC+8), duration_minutes (inclusive count of minutes), num_points, peak_deviation = max((value - P95)/ (P95+1e-12)) for high faults or max((P5 - value)/(abs(P5)+1e-12)) for low faults, peak_value (max value for high, min value for low), threshold_used (P95 for high, P5 for low). Store the full faults table in kernel variable metric_faults_full. Return two compact outputs only: (A) top 20 faults sorted by peak_deviation descending (columns as above) and (B) a per-component summary table (limit top 20) listing cmdb_id, total_faults (count of fault segments for that cmdb_id), earliest_fault_start (the minimum start_ts among its faults). Ensure timestamps are shown in UTC+8 and both returned tables are at most 20 rows. Keep full intermediate results in kernel variables but do not print them." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We grouped per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) anomalous rows inside the incident window into consecutive-minute faults and produced (A) a top-20 faults table ranked by peak_deviation and (B) a per-component summary ranked by total fault segments. Results show widespread short faults across many services and nodes. The highest fault counts are on frontend-0/1/2, checkoutservice-1/0/2, productcatalogservice-*, and multiple node metrics (node-6, node-5, node-2). Many series have P95 or P5 equal to zero, producing inflated deviation ratios; these require cautious interpretation. According to the fault table, node-6 and several checkoutservice/productcatalogservice metrics (including container network and memory failure KPIs) and mesh traffic KPIs are prominent. To localize root causes for the two distinct failures, we must (1) focus trace analysis on the top service candidates (to find downstream-most faulty services in call chains) and (2) check whether trace error_rate / row_count / duration anomalies align with metric faults and their earliest timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From kernel variable comp_summary_top20, select the top 10 cmdb_id components that are NOT node-* (i.e., service/pod names). Return that list.\n2) Using trace.csv (full available series) compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) over the full trace series (no time filtering). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 (inclusive) to 2022-03-21 08:00:00 (exclusive) UTC+8.\n3) From the filtered traces, keep only rows where either: (a) cmdb_id is in the top-10 non-node components from step 1, OR (b) trace_name contains any of those top-10 component names (to include to_/from_ traces involving them).\n4) For each remaining (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: count_high = count of rows with value > P95; earliest_high_ts; count_low = count of rows with value < P5; earliest_low_ts; P95; P5. Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id,trace_name) rows sorted by max(count_high,count_low) descending, with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count_high, earliest_high_ts, count_low, earliest_low_ts, P95, P5. Also return the total number of distinct trace series scanned in this filtered set and the number of series with at least one anomaly (count_high>0 or count_low>0).\nKeep all intermediate full tables in kernel variables (e.g., trace_thresholds_full, trace_filtered_candidates) but limit the printed return to the compact outputs above (max 20 rows). Timestamps must be in UTC+8."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous step we computed trace thresholds and filtered trace rows involving the top non-node components. The trace analysis found many anomalous trace series in the window (832 series scanned, 536 with anomalies) and showed that several services (e.g., adservice, shippingservice, frontend variants, recommendationservice, productcatalogservice) have trace anomalies with earliest occurrences around 07:30 and later. Metric fault segmentation produced a per-component fault count and earliest fault start time; many services show earliest faults at 07:30, while node-level metrics (node-6, node-5, node-2, etc.) also show faults with various earliest times (some around 07:30, others later). We still need to (A) separate the telemetry into the two distinct failure events (by time clustering), and (B) for each event determine the most likely root-cause component and reason by combining metric fault earliest timestamps, severity, and trace anomalies (to identify the most downstream faulty service). To proceed, we should produce a compact per-component summary from the metric faults that helps us identify which service/pod or node first showed a fault and which KPI was most frequently implicated — this will allow us to split the window into the two failures and pick the top candidates for trace/log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel variable metric_faults_full, produce two compact summary tables (timestamps in UTC+8):\n1) Service/Pod summary: consider only rows where cmdb_id does NOT match '^node-\\d+$'. For each cmdb_id compute: total_faults (count of fault segments), earliest_fault_start (minimum start_ts), top_fault_kpi (the kpi_name with the largest number of fault segments for that cmdb_id), top_kpi_faults_count, and top_kpi_earliest_start (earliest start_ts among faults for that top_fault_kpi). Return up to 20 rows sorted by earliest_fault_start ascending (earliest first).\n2) Node summary: consider only rows where cmdb_id matches '^node-\\d+$'. For each node compute the same columns as above (total_faults, earliest_fault_start, top_fault_kpi, top_kpi_faults_count, top_kpi_earliest_start). Return up to 20 rows sorted by earliest_fault_start ascending.\nReturn both compact tables and the total number of distinct components in each table. Keep the full computed summary tables in kernel variables (e.g., comp_fault_summary_services, comp_fault_summary_nodes) but limit printed output to the two compact tables (max 20 rows each)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We produced per-series thresholds, detected anomalies in the incident window, segmented anomalies into consecutive-minute fault segments, and summarized faults per component and per node. The compact summaries show many components have earliest faults at 2022-03-21 07:30:00 +0800, and a smaller set of faults (notably node-6 IO/await/iowait and some container memory/network failure KPIs) appear later (around ~07:45–07:59). This suggests the 07:30–08:00 period likely contains at least two distinct failure events: an early-wave event starting at the window start (≈07:30) affecting many services (frontends, checkoutservice, productcatalogservice, etc.), and a later wave where node-level IO/CPU/iowait anomalies (node-6 and others) spike (≈07:45–07:59). We need to split the faults into time clusters so we can localize root causes per event and then use traces/logs to pick the most downstream faulty component for each event.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From kernel variable metric_faults_full perform a compact time-clustering summary:\n1) Count number of fault segments grouped by fault start minute (start_ts floored to minute) within the incident window 2022-03-21 07:30:00 (inclusive) to 2022-03-21 08:00:00 (exclusive) UTC+8. Return the top 10 minutes sorted by count descending, with columns [start_minute, fault_count].\n2) For the top two minutes from (1), return for each minute the top 5 cmdb_id components ranked by number of faults whose start_ts equals that minute. For each top component return: cmdb_id, faults_in_minute, the most common kpi_name among those faults (top_kpi) and its faults count, and earliest fault start_ts among that component's faults in that minute. Limit output to top 5 components per minute.\nKeep full intermediate tables in kernel variables (e.g., faults_by_minute, top_components_per_minute) but return only the compact outputs described (bounded rows, timestamps in UTC+8)."
}

I reviewed the telemetry analysis: early-wave anomalies around 07:30 show the largest KPI deviation on checkoutservice-1 with supporting TCP retransmission spikes (node-2), indicating a network retransmission issue affecting checkoutservice-1; the late concentrated spike around 07:58 shows strong node I/O / iowait saturation on node-6 coincident with widespread frontend/service latency, indicating node-level disk I/O pressure.

